    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<h2>tl;dr</h2>\n<p>Make your own multi-map by calling <code>Map#computeIfAbsent</code> to create a collection as your <em>value</em> object.</p>\n<pre class=\"lang-java prettyprint-override\"><code>Map &lt; String, Set &lt; String &gt; &gt; multiMap = new HashMap&lt;&gt;() ;\n</code></pre>\n<p>Add Alice as a one or more Members of Channel per your Question.</p>\n<pre class=\"lang-java prettyprint-override\"><code>multiMap.computeIfAbsent( &quot;Channel A&quot; , _ -&gt; new HashSet &lt;&gt;() ).add( &quot;Alice&quot; ); \n</code></pre>\n<h2>Multimap</h2>\n<p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multimap\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><em>Multimap</em></a> is the technical term for what you want.</p>\n<h3>Third-party libraries</h3>\n<p>You can obtain a Multimap implementation from third-party frameworks. Check <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Google_Guava\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><em>Google Guava</em></a> and <a href=\"https://eclipse.dev/collections/\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><em>Eclipse Collections</em></a>.</p>\n<h3>Roll-your-own</h3>\n<p>The <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/25/docs/api/java.base/java/util/Map.html#computeIfAbsent(K,java.util.function.Function)\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><code>computeIfAbsent</code></a> method added to <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/25/docs/api/java.base/java/util/Map.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><code>Map</code></a> interface in Java 8+ lets us create a basic multimap.</p>\n<p>Define a <code>Map</code> where <strong>the <em>value</em> type is a collection</strong>. Use a <code>Set</code> to eliminate duplicates, or a <code>List</code> to allow duplicates. Here we define our <em>value</em> type as <code>Set &lt; String &gt;</code>.</p>\n<pre class=\"lang-java prettyprint-override\"><code>Map &lt; String, Set &lt; String &gt; &gt; multiMap = new HashMap &lt;&gt;();\n</code></pre>\n<p>Add entries to that map.</p>\n<p>When adding entries, we pass a <strong>lambda that creates a new empty collection</strong> as our <em>value</em> object if not found. That is the point of calling <code>Map#computeIfAbsent</code>. Our lambda here is <code>( String _ ) -&gt; new HashSet &lt;&gt;()</code>.</p>\n<pre class=\"lang-java prettyprint-override\"><code>multiMap.computeIfAbsent( &quot;A&quot; , ( String theKey ) -&gt; new HashSet &lt;&gt;() ).add( &quot;Alice&quot; );\nmultiMap.computeIfAbsent( &quot;A&quot; , ( String theKey ) -&gt; new HashSet &lt;&gt;() ).add( &quot;Bob&quot; );\nmultiMap.computeIfAbsent( &quot;A&quot; , ( String theKey ) -&gt; new HashSet &lt;&gt;() ).add( &quot;Alice&quot; ); // Duplicate\nmultiMap.computeIfAbsent( &quot;B&quot; , ( String theKey ) -&gt; new HashSet &lt;&gt;() ).add( &quot;Carol&quot; );\n</code></pre>\n<p>Notice in code above that lambda syntax requires us to name the variable, here <code>theKey</code>. In this case, we ignore the variable. So the name is merely a distraction. In Java 22+, we can use an underscore character as the name of a variable that we ignore. See <a href=\"https://openjdk.org/jeps/456\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><em>JEP 456: Unnamed Variables &amp; Patterns</em></a>.</p>\n<pre class=\"lang-java prettyprint-override\"><code>multiMap.computeIfAbsent( &quot;A&quot; , ( String _ ) -&gt; new HashSet &lt;&gt;() ).add( &quot;Alice&quot; );\nmultiMap.computeIfAbsent( &quot;A&quot; , ( String _ ) -&gt; new HashSet &lt;&gt;() ).add( &quot;Bob&quot; );\nmultiMap.computeIfAbsent( &quot;A&quot; , ( String _ ) -&gt; new HashSet &lt;&gt;() ).add( &quot;Alice&quot; ); // Duplicate\nmultiMap.computeIfAbsent( &quot;B&quot; , ( String _ ) -&gt; new HashSet &lt;&gt;() ).add( &quot;Carol&quot; );\n</code></pre>\n<p>Syntactically, we can abbreviate our lambda to <code>_ -&gt; new HashSet &lt;&gt;()</code> by replacing <code>( String _ )</code> with merely <code>_</code>. But there is no benefit other than brevity; same results.</p>\n<pre class=\"lang-java prettyprint-override\"><code>multiMap.computeIfAbsent( &quot;A&quot; , _ -&gt; new HashSet &lt;&gt;() ).add( &quot;Alice&quot; );\nmultiMap.computeIfAbsent( &quot;A&quot; , _ -&gt; new HashSet &lt;&gt;() ).add( &quot;Bob&quot; );\nmultiMap.computeIfAbsent( &quot;A&quot; , _ -&gt; new HashSet &lt;&gt;() ).add( &quot;Alice&quot; ); // Duplicate\nmultiMap.computeIfAbsent( &quot;B&quot; , _ -&gt; new HashSet &lt;&gt;() ).add( &quot;Carol&quot; );\n</code></pre>\n<p>Dump to console.</p>\n<pre class=\"lang-java prettyprint-override\"><code>multiMap.entrySet().forEach( IO :: println );  // Before Java 25, replace `IO` with `System.out`.\n</code></pre>\n<p>Notice that our use of a <code>Set</code> eliminated the duplicate <em>Alice</em> entry.</p>\n<pre class=\"lang-none prettyprint-override\"><code>A=[Bob, Alice]\nB=[Carol]\n</code></pre>\n"
  } ],
